ce:section.ce:para:
The appropriate amount of Fe3O4@SiO2 nanoparticles incorporated in the OH-HNTs@N-GQDs@Fe3O4@MIP probe was investigated from 5.0 to 50.0 mg. The nanoprobe prepared using 10.0 mg of Fe3O4@SiO2 provided the best sensitivity (
                              Fig. S3
                           ). Larger amounts of Fe3O4@SiO2 provided lower sensitivity may be due to Fe3O4@SiO2 blocked the recognition sites. While, smaller amounts of Fe3O4@SiO2 produced low magnetic property which difficultly separated with a magnet. Thus, the OH-HNTs@N-GQDs@Fe3O4@MIP probe was prepared using 10.0 mg of Fe3O4@SiO2 nanoparticles.

The quenching mechanism can be described by the Stern-Volmer equation [27]; F0/F = 1 + Ksv[Cmarbofloxacin], where F0 and F are the fluorescence intensity of the probe in the absence and presence of marbofloxacin, respectively, Ksv is the Stern-Volmer constant for marbofloxacin and [Cmarbofloxacin] is the concentration of the quencher (marbofloxacin). The obtained Stern-Volmer relationship was linear, which implied that a dynamic quenching caused by electron transfer. In the absence of marbofloxacin, electrons of N-GQDs excited from the ground state by UV light could return to the valence band by emitting fluorescence. In the presence of marbofloxacin, the NH2 groups of the monomer interacted with marbofloxacin via hydrogen bonding. The interaction induced electron transfer from N-GQDs to marbofloxacin, quenching the emission of fluorescence. In addition, the UV absorption spectrum of marbofloxacin did not overlap with the emission spectrum of the OH-HNTs@N-GQDs@Fe3O4@MIP probe (

                           Fig. S4

                        ), implying that energy transfer was not a possible quenching mechanism [28].
